	base stations. We show analytically that cooperatively scheduled
	
	transmission, which is well within the capability of present
	
	systems, can achieve an expanded multiuser diversity gain in
	
	terms of ergodic capacity as well as almost the same amount of
	
	interference reduction as conventional frequency reuse. This capacity
	
	gain over conventional frequency reuse is O(Mt logNs)
	
	for dirty paper coding and O(min(Mr,Mt) logNs) for time
	
	division, where Ns is the number of cooperating base stations
	
	employing opportunistic scheduling in an Mt  Mr MIMO
	
	system.
	
